{"title_page": "Scott Fitzgerald (boxer)", "text_new": "{{short description|English boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name        = Scott Fitzgerald\n| image       = \n| realname    =\n| nickname    = The Mad Man<br>Fitzy<br> \n| weight      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Light-middleweight]]\n*[[Middleweight]]\n}}\n| height       = 5 ft 10 in\n| reach       = 70 in\n| nationality = British\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|13 December 1991}}\n| birth_place = [[Preston, Lancashire]], England\n| style       = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total       = 14\n| wins        = 14\n| KO          = 9\n| losses      = 0\n| draws       = \n| no contests = \n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Boxing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold  | [[Boxing at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Boxing at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Welterweight|Welterweight]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[ABA Championships|English National Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold  | [[ABA Championships|2013 Houghton-le-Spring]] | Light-middleweight}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[ABA Championships|English National Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze  | [[ABA Championships|2015 Liverpool]] | [[Boxing at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Welterweight|Welterweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Scott Fitzgerald''' (born 13 December 1991) is a British [[professional boxer]] who has held the [[British Boxing Board of Control|British]] [[Super welterweight|super-welterweight]] title since 2019. As an amateur, he won the gold medal in the [[welterweight]] division at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/commonwealth-games/28624892|title=Glasgow 2014: Scott Fitzgerald wins England's third boxing gold|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2 August 2014|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref> 2020 beat his girl friend up while pregnant with second child and courting a 17 year old\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=9\n|ko-losses=\n|dec-wins=5\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|14\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|14\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Ted Cheeseman]]\n|UD\n|12\n|19 Oct 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Utilita Arena, Newcastle, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won [[List of British super-welterweight boxing champions|British super-welterweight title]]}} \n|-\n|13\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|13\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Anthony Fowler]]\n|SD\n|10\n|30 Mar 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Echo Arena, Liverpool, England}}\n|align=left|{{small|Won vacant [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International [[super-welterweight]] title}} \n|-\n|12\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|12\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|POL}} Filip Rzadek\n|TKO\n|2 (6), {{small|1:24}}\n|2 Feb 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[The O2 Arena]], [[London]], England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|11\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|11\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Craig Morris\n|TKO\n|10 (10), {{small|2:13}}\n|8 Sep 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Arena Birmingham]], [[Birmingham]], England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|10\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|10\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|HUN}} Laszlo Fazekas\n|PTS\n|8\n|21 Apr 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Echo Arena, Liverpool, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|9\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|9\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|GHA}} Ishmael Tetteh\n|TKO\n|1 (6), {{small|2:10}}\n|25 Feb 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Victoria Warehouse Hotel, Manchester, En