\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite news |title=Betty Blythe Dead at 78 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49356165/betty-blythe-dead-at-78/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=The Des Moines Register |date=April 9, 1972}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1964\n| ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]''\n| Lady at Ball (uncredited)\n|Warner Bros.\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web |title=My Fair Lady |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/22921-MY-FAIR-LADY?cxt=filmography|website=catalog.afi.com|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|- align=\"center\"\n! colspan=5 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Television\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Title\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Role\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Network/notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\"  |{{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1952\n| ''[[Racket Squad]]''\n| Mrs. Burton\n| 1 episode, [[CBS]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web |title=Racket Squad |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/racket-squad/episode-26-season-2/the-case-of-the-hearse-chasers/203929/ |website=TVGuide.com |accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1958\n| ''[[The Lineup (TV series)|The Lineup]]''\n| Mrs. DeSues\n| 1 episode, CBS\n|align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite news |title=Film Vamp of '25 Gets TV Bit Part |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49369071/film-vamp-of-25-gets-tv-bit-part/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=The Times-Tribune |date=April 5, 1958}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|title=Betty Blythe, Who Starred in Silent Films, Dead on Coast|work=New York Times|date=9 April 1972}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category|Betty Blythe}}\n*{{IMDb name|0090029}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{amg name|6923}}\n*[http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/6659/betty-blythe Betty Blythe] at Virtual History\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blythe, Betty}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Betty Blythe\n| image = Betty Blythe Stars of the Photoplay.jpg\n| imagesize = 190px\n| caption = Blythe in 1924\n| birth_name = Elizabeth Blythe Slaughter\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1893|9|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1972|4|7|1893|9|1|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1916&ndash;1964\n| occupation = Actress\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Paul Scardon]]|1919|1954|end=died}}\n}}\n\n'''Betty Blythe''' (born '''Elizabeth Blythe Slaughter''';<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eSIhzKnNUf4C&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=elizabeth+blythe+slaughter&source=bl&ots=C7NLH5vjpL&sig=ACfU3U3tFcoc7e740pv5779jzEgL3Z0wTw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3oevq8NvoAhVLnq0KHe00COk4ChDoATANegQICRAB|title=Dictionary of Pseudonyms: 13,000 Assumed Names and Their Origins, 5th ed.|first=Adrian|last=Room|date=January 10, 2014|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref> September 1, 1893 &ndash; April 7, 1972) was an American actress best known for her dramatic roles in exotic [[silent film]]s such as ''[[The Queen of Sheba (1921 film)|The Queen of Sheba]]'' (1921).  She appeared in 63 silent films and 56 talkies over the course of her career.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/betty-blythe/|title=Betty Blythe|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nShe was born Elizabeth Blythe Slaughter in Los Angeles, where she attended [[Harvard-Westlake School|Westlake School for Girls]], and the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Betty Blythe One of Ansonia Stars |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49387910/betty-blythe-one-of-ansonia-stars/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=The Anaconda Standard |date=January 25, 1919 |pages=4}}</ref> Betty had already shortened her name to Betty Blythe when she and three other women posed for a photo shoot of the newest swim fashion for women, a bathing suit.  Prior to then, women were expected to wear stockings with full dresses or  skirts into the water.<ref>{{cite news |title=These Girls Won't Risk Their Lives By Wearing Old Style Bathing Suits |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49389946/these-girls-wont-risk-their-lives-by/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=The Sacramento Star |date=August 10, 1915}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Nomads of the North.jpg|right|thumb|[[Film still|Still]] (''left to right)'' of [[Melbourne MacDowell]], [[Lon Chaney]] and Blythe in ''[[Nomads of the North]]'', 1920]]\nBlythe began her stage work in such theatrical pieces as ''So Long Letty'' and ''The Peacock Princess''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/betty-blythe-32348|title=Betty Blythe \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff &#124; IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com}}</ref> She worked in vaudeville as the \"California Nightingale\" singing songs such as \"Love Tales from Hoffman\".\n\nIn 1915, she had an unbilled part in ''[[Bella Donna (1915 film)|Bella Donna]]'' for [[Famous Players Film Company]].  After her first [[Vitagraph Studios]] role in the 1917 vehicle, she was given a leading role in the studio's 1918 film ''A Game With Fate''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Morey and Betty Blythe as Queen Friday and Saturday |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49380521/harry-morey-and-betty-blythe-as-queen/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=Austin American-Statesman |date=September 5, 1918}}</ref>\n\nAs famous for her revealing costumes as for her dramatic skills, she became a star in such exotic films as [[The Queen of Sheba (1921 film)|''The Queen of Sheba'']] (1921) (in which she wore nothing above the waist except a string of beads),<ref name=Pearls>{{cite news |title=Betty Blythe, Screen Star of Silent 'Queen of Sheba' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49434194/betty-blythe-screen-star-of-silent/ |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=April 9, 1972}}</ref> ''[[Chu-Chin-Chow (1925 film)|Chu-Chin-Chow]]'' (made in 1923; released by MGM in the US 1925) and ''[[She (1925 film)|She]]'' (1925). She was also seen to good advantage in less revealing films like ''[[Nomads of the Nor th]]'' (1920) with [[Lon Chaney]] and ''[[In Hollywood with Potash and Perlmutter]]'' (1924), produced by [[Samuel Goldwyn]].Other roles were as an opera star, unbilled in Garbo's ''[[The Mysterious Lady]]''. She continued to work as a character actress. One of her last roles was a small uncredited role in a crowd scene in 1964's ''[[My Fair Lady]]''.<ref name=Pearls/> \n\n==Personal life==\nBlythe was married to the movie director [[Paul Scardon]] from 1919 until his death in 1954.  She reportedly made $3,500,000 when she sold a section of land that is now part of the Sunset Strip.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She lost her fortune in the 1929 stock market crash.<ref name=\"auto\"/> She died of a heart attack in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles, California|Woodland Hills, California]] in 1972, aged 78. She is buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]] in [[Glendale, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOHgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA70&lpg=PA70&dq=elizabeth+blythe+slaughter&source=bl&ots=UkWHQDzGJ4&sig=ACfU3U3MXsbd51ZM8bdUxFqtKC5hQKqgIg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi-idqO8dvoAhUMKKwKHSfACag4FBDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=elizabeth+blythe+slaughter&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|first=Scott|last=Wilson|date=August 19, 2016|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref> \n\n==Awards and memorials==\nFor her contributions to the film industry, Betty Blythe has a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] located at 1708 [[Vine Street]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/betty-blythe |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame - Betty Blythe |website=walkoffame.com |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer name lives on through the Betty Blythe Vintage Tea Room in [[West Kensington]], London, England.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome To Betty Blythe |url=http://www.bettyblythe.co.uk/ |website=Betty Blythe |accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\n\n\nFile:Belladonna-newspaper-scene-1915.jpg|[[Belladonna]] L-R, L'Estrange, Blythe, Frederick\nFile:Betty Blythe Queen of Sheba adjusted.jpg|Queen of Sheba\nFile:Betty Blythe - The Queen of Sheba - Movie Stars Postcard Set.jpg|Queen of Sheba Poster\nFile:Photoplay September 1921 - Betty Blythe.jpg|Photoplay cover\nFile:Betty Blythe 2 - Dec 1919 Shadowland.jpg|Shadowland\nFile:The Darling of the Rich (1922) - 1.jpg|Darling of the Rich advertisement\n\n</gallery>\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! colspan=5 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film credits of Betty Blythe\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\"| Year\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" width = 35% | Title\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\"width = 25% | Role\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Studio/Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\"  |{{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1915\n| ''[[Bella Donna (1915 film)|Bella Donna]]''\n| dancer (uncredited)\n|[[Famous Players Film Company]]\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n!s